segments.text: Nicknames for the president's quarters.
One of them was David Morgan.
It was called the House of David.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Let's see.
Gilchrist?
Not very late.
Harrington?
Uncle Tom's cat.
Oh, okay.
Very good, very good.
Rudder?
The General's Shack, I wonder, or something like that.
I don't know.
I don't recall.
Describe how the students' relations with a faculty member.
What was their manner, their style, if they came to your office?
Were they respectful?
Oh, yes.
Always respectful.
Always, yes, sir.
Cooperative.
We helped a good many student conferences.
Actually, we required the head of the department.
Not only a requirement, it was something we wanted to do.
But, oh yes, they were always respectful.
Even Murray Trimble.
Remember Murray Trimble?
A fine football player.
He lost a hand?
He lost a hand, yeah.
He got in big trouble and finally got expelled.
He was a bit of a roughneck, but I had Murray in class.
During those years, particularly the 50s and 60s, describe for me a typical work week for you.
Normally you left here and got to the office...
About what time?
Well, usually I make a class.
We talk quite a number of hours.
Pretty much classes and conferences pretty much took up my day.
So you, did you walk over or drive?
I drove more often than you'd think, actually.
So you'd leave here at about what time?
The students, and your work day, so you were, as far as you recall, by the late 50s, what was a normal teaching load?
When did it go down from 18 hours?
About 15 hours.
About 15.
About 15.
And about how many of those were introductory courses and how many advanced?
Do you remember?
Well, actually, the English department was still the service department.
We didn't have any graduate courses.
Senior level was as far as we went.
No, it was a question.
No, about how many of them were junior, senior compared to the introductory freshman
Well, we've had a great many more freshman sections.
I can't give you any specific numbers really, but we had more freshman sections because everyone had taken these freshman composition and maybe the sophomore literature course.
Above that, a number were taken as electives, so of course there were fewer.
In the English department, what were some of the popular elective courses?
Well, quite a few took the technical ride.
A lot of students thought that was useful to them, and a lot of them took that as a popular course.
Then a rather surprising number elected to Shakespeare.
And then other than that, I think probably both the American Lit Survey and the English Lit Survey.
What were your favorite sections to teach?
Well, I was always interested in the American Literature and I taught all of that.
I taught a novelist course and I taught the American Literature survey, but we taught across the board.
I taught technical writing.
I even taught speech class.
So, you would leave here, leave the house... Well, I worked between 7.30 and 8 and almost always had an 8 o'clock class.
I drove that short distance a good deal of the time.
So I wouldn't arrive there trenched in sweat.
Where did you park?
In the academic building parking lot.
There was no big deal about parking in those days.
And there was no fee.
No fee.
Did you come home for lunch?
Yes.
And then you went back, and normally your day on the campus would end at about what time?
Oh, maybe very gorgeous classes I have there.
Three or four o'clock.
And six-day week, because it's Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday.
What did you and your family, what the social life, as the girls got a little older, what did you all do in the community?
Well, of course, they were wrapped up in school activities, and we did all the PTA stuff.
And of course, we went to all the athletic events, and any concert or play or anything that we could find.
Where were the concerts and the plays held on the campus?
Guyon Hall.
And make believe that I had never been in Guyon Hall.
Describe it for me.
Well, it was sort of a Greek.
The Greek Revival started a lovely old building, and I really hated to see it built.
And it seated 1,200 men?
About 1,200 men.
They had religious emphasis week in those days.
Filled it up for those services.
Do you remember some famous people that came to speak or perform?
Well, I certainly should, but I'm afraid I don't.
because I've heard some of the students talk about the big bands that came and performed in Sabisa for their dances.
Who were the, in the 50s, who were the key administrators?
Who was the dean of arts and sciences during those years?
I knew that was coming.
Was Dr. Abbott in there?
I suspect so.
And then Frank Hubert comes in 59.
Yeah.
All right, let's talk about him.
Describe him as the dean.
He was very effective.
He took some ribbing in there about having been an high school band director and so on, but he was very approachable and very effective.
Mr. Rutter comes in January of 59.
Were there any faculty comments about his selection, his appointment?
as you recall.
What about David Morgan?
How did the faculty see him?
Well, I think that there was some satisfaction that an outsider, so to speak, had.
I don't remember really what things he did, but I think he had a pretty high approval rating.
I got here at about the same time Mr. Rutter did, and at first I wasn't impressed with Mr. Rutter's academic style and ability, but I later came to realize that he had many other abilities.
Let's see, describe College Station in the 50s and 60s as a very separate town.
Well, it, of course, was still very small, and I think people felt very close and felt very safe.
Dr. Morgan went to California every summer to read in the Huntington Library, and I remember one summer he was leaving, and I said, well, if you need anything, you know,
And people I presume have always parked over here.
and for football games.
Have you ever had any incidents, problems on a football weekend of somebody that parked in front of the house and bothered anything?
No.
Never?
They're really regulating that now.
But never many times have we had that.
Back to campus, who are some of the key individuals that you, other than maybe
the president and so forth, some other key individuals that you think helped make A&M in the 50s, 60s, 70s?
Advisors, counselors, administrators?
Wayne Stark.
Yeah, Wayne Stark.
What role did he play that made the thing better?
Really had tremendous influence.
He involved so many students at the Memorial Student Center.
Taught them so much, actually, by involving them in the activities.
He made all kinds of trips, taking students to cultural events.
said they don't have.
Tremendous influence.
It made all the difference in the world.
Did you ever go on any of those?
Yes.
Describe one of those.
Well, I remember going to Houston to and we met with John Lindsey.
Lindsey, yeah, John Lindsey.
Thereafter, he took us to a club, to which he built a home, and we just did the job.
I had some drinks.
What was the effect on the students of that weekend?
Well, I think they were a little bit awestruck.
But I think they enjoyed it.
I think that for, we got to go on one of those, and I got the impression that this was almost like helping those students to raise their sights.
that you could become able to enjoy this kind of art and culture and so forth?
Yeah, I think he had that.
Pinky Downs.
Yeah, I met Pinky almost as soon as I arrived.
I think I was in the campus post office.
He came up, hi, I'm Pinky Downs.
Where are you from?
And Pinky always gave his prediction that the bonfire was going to be Texas.
Now, before the MSC is built, what was the center for extracurricular activities?
Well, basically there wasn't anything.
Certainly back when we came here, when the girls came down from Texas University for dances and stuff, they had a rough time.
Couldn't find a bathroom.
And it wasn't a whole lot better until we came to get the center.
I suppose it's pretty simple.
And there were a few activities at the old YMCA, I understand.
Yes, there were some at the YMCA.
Was Mr. Cashin still active?
Yes, yes.
I know nothing about him.
Please tell about him.
Well, I really don't remember too much about himself.
He was a much-loved person, I know.
A lot of students flocked to the YMCA.
I know he did a lot of counseling, but I suppose, in a sense, he was one of those key figures.
Where did a student in the 50s and 60s, where did a student go for advice, counsel?
I have the belief that in that era, faculty members thought that one of their unwritten responsibilities was to be a counselor in addition to being
a teacher that teaching extended far beyond the classroom.
Yeah, I think so.
I've been proud of A&M on that score.
I think that attitude has been there.
We tried to make personal contact with students.
Actually, I think we're still trying, although it's pretty tough.
All right, we were talking about presidents.
Jack Williams, what was your impression of him and his role as president here?
Well, I was very favorably impressed with him.
He was one I knew, more or less.
Certainly had a rather high opinion.
Had a tough time health-wise.
What do you think were some, in your, let's see, what, 40 years?
How long I taught?
Yeah.
Well, I taught for 32 years.
Yeah.
Well, my slot was 46 to 78.
Oh, okay.
And I've had 21 years since then to forget things.
Right.
During those years...
if there were people that you could pull out and thank them and pat them, who were those people that made a difference for this school?
Well, I suppose all the presidents did to some extent.
I mean, William Stark certainly made a difference around here.
Do any of the presidents, do you have any favorites among them?
What are some of the key decisions you think that were made during, that were very important to A&M today?
Well, we integrated for one thing.
I remember very well when we conducted the summer school enrollment speech of all.
It was a long table.
And the word was passed along to us, there will be black students enrolled in the role, and it was a peaceful museum.
And then somebody made that decision.
And of course, eventually, the commission went on.
Do you remember any, even a hint of an incident over integration?
I don't either.
Yeah, that was much easier than burning the windows.
I now know that Mr.
Rudder was a key person in getting those students here that summer because he called the Pentagon and had them send, as they normally would send, Army personnel to finish a degree.
And I now know that he called and said, send some, including some black students, no academic danger, no conduct problem.
And then when the fall began, since everything had gone well in the summer,
someone couldn't organize a group, say it won't work.
It had worked.
Do you remember, as women began, do you remember any kinds of, any incidents or awkward moments or pranks?
No, I don't think anything much happened until the melodies and business came along.
Speaking of the Pentagon, one of my brightest black students was a Marine, and he was from Maine.
We were back from the New England trip, and I said, we're going to our country.
We're going to Bar Harbor.
You mean Bahama.
He was a regular Marine.
Yes, he was.
And he had been sent here.
We've been sent here.
I was surprised, but there he was.
Let's see.
We mentioned coeducation, integration, non-compulsory core.
Do you remember the beginning of the graduate program in English?
Yes.
How did it come about?
Well, it began in the late 50s, and we began to, we worked with Dean Buber on that, and began to talk about it.
I believe, Steve John... Abbott?
I swear that name escapes me.
I believe he was head at the time.
Okay.
And we talked with David Burton and he talked about perhaps starting a private program, maybe in American literature only.
Well, we wanted to go farther than that, of course, and we did.
So we dug into it, and we had to have a biography of each professor who would teach a regular course, and so on.
We fought all that out in the 1950s.
And were there any snags, as you remember?
Or did it pretty well go forward?
Well, it pretty well went along.
I don't recall any major snags.
And when did the doctoral program, were you still a faculty member when the doctoral program began?
Yes.
any key people that deserve a pat on the back there?
Well, certainly this department head worked like a tiger in Washington today.
And Lee Martin was very active.
Was Maxwell the dean by this time?
David Maxwell?
No, we had that before Maxwell.
Oh, okay.
So it would still have been Hubert, I guess.
Was English one of the pioneer
humanities, social sciences graduate area?
I believe so.
I think so.
Let's see.
Do you remember anything that students ever did to go out of their way to be polite or show appreciation for anything?
I don't believe so, beyond coming up at the end and saying, enjoy the course, that kind of thing.
Did any student or parent of a student ever attempt to intimidate you?
Unless my student, my son, passes this or that, did anybody ever attempt to in any way bribe you with anything?
No, never did.
I only had one parent-student incident whatsoever.
I had a student who was about 25 years old who was in a technical writing class.
And he didn't hand in his term paper.
He didn't show up for the examination.
And actually he just disappeared.
I got the call from the parent to see if I had any idea what he was.
But I didn't.
So I got, I don't remember who I got in touch with, but I got in touch with some authority.
I said, we have a student who apparently disappeared.
Well, about three days later, they discovered him hiding out in a dorm.
There was something wrong with the young man.
He certainly, in age, won't pass away.
He was scared to death.
He had me in on that paper.
He was scared to come to the exam.
And his father came up here, and I remember meeting with the father in the state.
I wasn't going to matter to him.
He got in touch later, and I eventually let him finish the paper.
And I believe he came back and took the exam.
Do you recall any what you now in hindsight think of as administrative interference with the way the academic program was operated in English?
In terms of was there a merit salary system?
Yes.
And the promotions were handled, as far as you were concerned, with reasonable fairness and equity?
Who are some special students that you remember now with pride and joy?
Well, I've always been.
I've always been fond of Dick.
Of course, he's a very successful attorney.
He's in San Antonio now.
I had Jack Pardee as a student.
Oh, did you?
Describe him as a student.
Well, Jack, I had him in only this one class.
And he was very respectful.
Big man on campus, but he didn't throw any weight around.
He was a good student.
And he'd gone to a small high school.
Because he was a...
Yes.
Jack made it be, as I recall, a technical writing class, well-deserved.
Certainly very pleasant.
I have written to him a time or two.
He did something notable.
And I had Henry Cisneros.
Was he a good student?
Oh, excellent student.
I would have expected him.
He was an A student.
I'm just...
Sorry he's had troubles.
Let's go back to Pardee for a second.
Did, under Bear Bryant, was there ever any, did anybody ever tried to influence you in grading an athlete?
Not directly, but he had a scholastic advisor.
Jerry Claiborne?
Jerry Claiborne, who later coached where, I don't remember.
Kentucky?
Kentucky, yeah.
Anyway, Jerry would come around and ask how the students were getting along.
He would stand there and twirl his 5-8 cap of tea and say, how's this?
He never really put any pressure.
Did any other coach ever, in any sport, ever attempt to ask for any special favors?
Not for me.
Did anyone in the Corps?
And you didn't hear about any board member's son or any general's son?
No, I didn't.
No, I guess I was lucky.
Other special students, you mentioned Stick Stengel and Jack Pardee, others that you remember with pride?
Well, I remember way back there was Jim Pye, the one I mentioned that was involved with computers.
He's done extremely well.
I haven't heard from him for a long time.
He's a senior engineer with ABN.
I remember him.
Did you become involved with any extracurricular student groups?
Oh yes, I remember students from that, yeah.
Oh yeah, I did a lot of that.
I coached Dubey, and I was on the, I worked with Scola for years, and I was on the MSC Council.
I remember, I remember Chet Edwards was one of them.
He was a guest representative.
From Waco and Temple, yes.
I remember Chet very well.
Oh, I remember.
John Rogers, he was a pagan in the insurance company in Dallas.
Bud Whitney actually started this corner.
And then there was John Samuels, the New York millionaire.
He was the sponsor of the opera and all that sort of thing.
He was one of my debaters.
If you could go back, this is a very broad question, if you could go back and make any changes in decisions or procedures, what would you change, being blessed with hindsight?
I was asking you to offer advice based on your experience, anything you would have changed then and or advice to give to leaders now about A&M.
Well, I would have tried to change then and would suggest changing now.
It would make an effort to broaden the student experience.
It's always...
bothered me the whole time I was here, that the attitude seemed to be to train people rather than to broadly educate them.
To broadly educate them was what I think ought to be done.
And if there are aspirations to be a top ten university, some of that has to come.
I would think that would be an impossibility unless we added something in the fine arts
During those years that you were active on the campus, who were the key people whom you thought were most sensitive to this need to broaden and to deepen?
Well, I guess all English faculty felt that way, and I'm sure that some of the other people in liberal arts did.
What about key campus leaders?
Well, I think David Maxwell would like very much to have done that, definitely.
And it seems to me that Jack Williams had that attitude.
